                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top of page, in black ink by an early modern hand, a note on the timeline of St Birgitta's life and a quotation from book 4 of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102572">Martín del Río</persName>'s <quote>Disquisitionum magicarum libri sex</quote>, published in 1599, reporting the view of the theologians <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102574">Henry of Langenstein</persName> and <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102575">Bartholomaeus Sibylla</persName> on the status of Birgitta's revelations:<quote> I. N. I. Delrius l. 4 disquis. Magicar. c. i. q. 3. s. 4. Henricus de Hassia et Sibyllanus ambo Catholici ambo religiosi volunt Brigittae et similium revelationes non debere haberi pro indubitanter veris. Claruit Brigitta haec circa annum C. 1350. Vide Fasc. Temp. f. cxxi a. Vixit in anno 1370. Vide Rev. l. 4. c. 41. Anno 1373 l. 4. c. 45 paulo post mortua l. 4. c. 57.</quote>; below, in pencil by a modern
                                    hand, a note on the acquisition:<quote> Inköpt på auktion i Lyon 1891, dec. Anländ t. Sthlm och betald 1892 jan. Inskr<supplied reason="omitted">iven</supplied> s<supplied reason="omitted">amma</supplied> å<supplied reason="omitted">r</supplied>
                                    </quote>; below, in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>Pericaud 1696 p 94</quote>; below, in pencil by a modern hand, the current signum of the National Library: <quote>A 66</quote>; below, in brown ink by a medieval hand:<quote> liber sancte Marie uirginis in lubene Celestium reuelacionum domine Brigitte</quote>; below, in pencil by an early modern hand: <quote>Anno domini 1418</quote>; bottom left corner, National Library book label with the current signum.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Bottom centre in brown ink by a medieval hand: <quote>X fo. perg.</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Red leather over wooden boards; the red dye may not be original, as it covers several holes in the leather and part of the medieval book label. 5 double raised bands and endbands. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>, 5 round corner and centre metal bosses. 2 pin clasps, originally with leather straps, the remaining one with traces of red dye. The clasp is in a shape resembling a knight chess piece facing outwards. Top centre, contemporary parchment label with the title: <quote>liber reuelationum brigittae</quote>. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in black ink by an early modern hand: <quote>S. Brig[ittae liber reuelationum?]</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 66</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="315" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="235" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="90" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>Leather worn, some holes coloured over with red dye. The front cover has been separated from the spine. 1 clasp and strap missing.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
